title: For Sale:  Exc. WWII Springfield M1
postcontent: This is an excellent condition and all correct WWII Springfield Armory M1 Garand in .30-06. The serial number on this M1 is 1946863, which places its date of manufacture in September 1943. The receiver has 98%+ of its original gray-green parkerized finish. The barrel is also Springfield manufactured and is SA marked and dated "9-43," so it is the original barrel for this rifle. The bore is excellent with a mirror bore and it gauges at 0.5 at the muzzle and about 2.5 at the throat so it is simply superb. The gas hole is correctly parkerized and the majority of the original parkerized finish remains on the barrel. The Rear Sight has the correct Type 1C Elevation Knob with knurled knob and closed arrow heads, Type 2B Lock Bar and Type 2 Rear Sight Cover. The Bolt is a correct -12SA Springfield bolt with the majority of its original parkerized finish and with wear on the friction points. The Operating Rod is an original, uncut and correct Type 5 "D35382 6SA" rod in excellent condition. The Follower Rod is a correct Type 4 "short fork" ribbed and riveted. The Operating Rod Catch is a correct Type 2. The Follower Arm is a correct Type 4 with rounded shoulders. The Follower is a correct Type 2C marked "11" on the bottom. The Bullet Guide is a correct Type 3 forged and milled with the wide slot. The Trigger Housing is a correct Type 8, -12SA marked with the majority of its original parkerized finish remaining. The Trigger Guard is the correct Type 1G, milled, that is unmarked. The Trigger is a correct Type 2 with no tooling hole and "S" mark. The Hammer is a correct Type 2D, -5SA marked. The Hammer Spring Plunger is a correct Type I with no rims on the sides. The Hammer Spring Housing is a correct Type 2. The Safety is a correct Type 3B, -9SA marked with most of the original parkerized finish remaining. The Gas Cylinder is a correct Type 2C, unmarked, wide, that has been field painted over (this part is stainless and GIs found that it would not take a parkerized finish and would turn silvery bright and they would use all kinds of things to reduce glare and keep this part dark).

title: For Sale:  .223 federal
postcontent:
To those of you reselling the ammo for profit, I'd be careful if I were you.
You are basically operating a business with no license, no FFL from the BATF, and you aren't paying state or local taxes on your sales.
You may get away with it a few times, but if you do it on a regular basis and attract too much attention, the IRS and BATFE just might catch on.

Besides the legality aspects, you are being assholes to the legal, legitimate businesses (especially the small local gun stores). They can't even get any sizable inventory to sell because it disappears from the larger stores that get the priority shipments, and it's all on the private individual market.
If you want to sell ammo do it the right way and get the proper licensing and certification like legitimate business owners do.
Otherwise get a 2nd job (or a job period) if you're that greedy.
It's pretty sad to imagine what it would be like if the shortage was food or gas instead of ammo. 
It's all about me, all about making a profit, no sh1t given about anyone else....even when it's ILLEGAL, ethics and morals aside.

While it would be a lot of fun to sell the Camp 10 as the ultimate zombie-whacking tool, the truth is, it actually has a lot of other uses that you just might find to be of a more immediate nature than zombie defense. title: For Sale:  Custom Rare Ruger 10/22 Folder with Packer Stock
postcontent:
Up for sale is a really odd, rare custom-built Ruger 10/22. I know there’s at least one other like it as it gave me the idea to make this one – but aside from these two, you may never find another.

I started with an older model 10/22 with the desirable cast trigger group housing. I added a Volquartsen hammer / sear kit, a bolt hold-open plate and an extended magazine release lever.

Then came the Butler Creek folding stock in blue.

Finally, the Butler Creek Packer forearm and barrel was added. These are nowhere to be found, production discontinued years ago. I used the forearm assembly / barrel clamp, which bolts to the receiver. I cut off the nose of the folding stock to accommodate the packer forearm. I then shaped the Packer forearm as best I could to the contours of the folding stock. I admit this is a bit amateurish, but the Packer stock is a different plastic, almost a rubber-like plastic and I never could get it scratch free or matte to match the folding stock.

The barrel came from the Packer stock set. It is unfired, made by Butler Creek and the one intended to be used with this stock forearm. It has the same rubbery plastic cover with steel liner.

I added a high scope mount, Burris 1” Quick Detachable rings and a new Nikon Rimfire 3x9 scope.

All folded up, the reciver and stock and scope is about 12” long *(13” overall with scope mounted). The barrel is 16.5 inches.  Total weight is around 6 pounds.

If you could even find the Butler Creek Packer stock kit (you can’t) it would cost you the absurd amount of $900 or so to reproduce this.

Everything locks up very tight. It's not super easy to break it down, but you sure don't want a loose sloppy barrel fit either.

I will knock off $150 from the price if you do not want the scope.

I can ship to your FFL or directly to another Texas resident for $25.00. I'll need some form of ID.

No felons, nobody under 21. FTF in Houston too. Need pics, ask; I have many ready to email.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mobile Barrel Threading and Crowning service.
location: Coos Bay North Bend Bandon Reedsport Coquille, Oregon Coast, Oregon
postcontent:
Is your hunting rifle or pistol inaccurate? 
Do your groups suck? 
Be honest lol. 
It might not be your fault, the damaged or worn out crown on your barrel could be responsible.
All of the pressure behind every fired round must exit the barrel evenly around the back of the bullet or it will send it wobbling or tumbling creating bad groups especially at longer distances.

Check out the before and after groups in the picture that where done with just a re-crown and no other mods or scope adjustments. I know it looks rigged but its not lol.

I don't sell anything but I can do modifications such as 90 degree target crowns, 11 degree recessed crowns, lighten triggers, modify feed ramps, barrel shorten and re-crown, barrel threading that allows for attachments such as flash hiders, legal sound suppressors, compensators and muzzle brakes that reduce felt recoil and muzzle climb etc...

Everything I do is completely legal according to state and federal laws AND...
Best part is I am mobile. Yes, believe it or not I can come to you or meet you somewhere and do these modifications while you watch and your gun never leaves your sight.
